  volume =        {25},
  year =          {2010},
  abstract =      {To an evolutionary geneticist, the most important
                   property of a new mutation is its effect on fitness.
                   Stress is a reduction in fitness that can also alter
                   the selection on new mutations. Although the effects
                   of environmental and genetic stresses are typically
                   studied separately, it is useful to consider them
                   from the same perspective. Here we evaluate the
                   common perception that stress increases selection. We
                   consider various conceptual paradigms for thinking
                   about selection and stress, and then review the
                   empirical data. We reject the notion that stress
                   typically increases selection. Instead, we find that
                   different types of stresses affect selection
                   differently, though the underlying mechanisms are, as
                   yet, unclear in most cases. {\textcopyright} 2010
